    "body": "Very cool, thanks. Based on your test failure, I ran a git bisect and confirmed that the issue came from commit 05254afe - exactly the one where I added all of the validation. It looks like there is nothing special about the object being used, it's just a placeholder. I think I prefer the the second solution, because then users are still protected from undefined/unexpected behaviour, like NPE if they call compareTo().\n\nThoughts?\n",

    "body": "The ticket is resolved, closing PR. \r\n \r\nPlease close PRs for your resolved tickets and other non-needed PRs. \r\n \r\nAlternatively, ask a committer \r\n- to use GitHub UI (committer can associate accounts here: https://gitbox.apache.org/setup/ )\r\n- or https://github.com/apache/ignite/blob/master/scripts/apply-pull-request.sh from Apache Ignite source.\r\n- or mention in commit message 'Fixes #(a number of PR)'. \r\n \r\nThese methods will automatically close PR.\r\n \r\nFeel free to reopen this PR if it is anyway actual.\r\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  }

    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Hey, I think we miss something important. The data sent to InfluxDB once also depend on the category of requests. That is, for example, if we define lots of different HTTP requests in one thread group and most of them are failed, the size of data sent to InfluxDB will increase a lot, because each failure will be a \"line protocol\".\r\n\r\nObviously it doesn't make sense restricting the category of requests, I think this PR also doesn't help resolve the problem. Sorry for not thinking comprehensively. Maybe we can find another way out.",

    "body": "Hey, I think we miss something important. The data sent to InfluxDB once also depend on the category of requests. That is, for example, if we define lots of different HTTP requests in one thread group and most of them are failed, the size of data sent to InfluxDB will increase a lot, because each failure will be a \"line protocol\".\r\n\r\nObviously it doesn't make sense restricting the category of requests, I think this PR also doesn't help resolve the problem. Sorry for not thinking comprehensively. Maybe we can find another way out.",

Sorry for not thinking comprehensively. Maybe we can find another way out.",

    "body": "Hey, I think we miss something important. The data sent to InfluxDB once also depend on the category of requests. That is, for example, if we define lots of different HTTP requests in one thread group and most of them are failed, the size of data sent to InfluxDB will increase a lot, because each failure will be a \"line protocol\".\r\n\r\nObviously it doesn't make sense restricting the category of requests, I think this PR also doesn't help resolve the problem. Sorry for not thinking comprehensively. Maybe we can find another way out.",

Sorry for not thinking comprehensively. Maybe we can find another way out.",

    "created_at": "2017-05-06T15:32:05Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-05-06T15:33:21Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "There are two methods for calculating percentile: Nearest Rank method and Linear Interpolation Between Closest Ranks method.\r\nMedian equal to percentile 50 if interpolation method is used. But for JMeter measuring purposes the nearest rank percentile should be used because perc 90 gives the exact maximum time (not interpolated with some other values) for 90% of tests and this is what JMeter users are expecting.\r\nThis is why the median should be calculated separately (or we can implement interpolation method and use it for particular median purpose).\r\nBy the way getPercentPoint method is [failing also](https://gist.github.com/abalanonline/9b128faa67e2459b765c1ef56454684b). I will raise a bug.\r\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "created_at": "2017-05-08T02:20:47Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-05-08T02:20:59Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Hello @pmouawad ,\r\nI investigated the HdrHistogram project. Unfortunately we cannot use it in JMeter right now.\r\n1. It do not have median method implemented.\r\n2. It do not have the interpolated percentile method either.\r\n3. It have the same bug calculating the 75th percentile of 11 data values {3, 6, 7, 8, 8, 9, 10, 13, 15, 16, 20} (example from Wikipedia)\r\n\r\nSo I suggest either fix the bugs in current org.apache.jorphan library.     "created_at": "2017-05-06T15:32:05Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-05-06T15:33:21Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "There are two methods for calculating percentile: Nearest Rank method and Linear Interpolation Between Closest Ranks method.\r\nMedian equal to percentile 50 if interpolation method is used. But for JMeter measuring purposes the nearest rank percentile should be used because perc 90 gives the exact maximum time (not interpolated with some other values) for 90% of tests and this is what JMeter users are expecting.\r\nThis is why the median should be calculated separately (or we can implement interpolation method and use it for particular median purpose).\r\nBy the way getPercentPoint method is [failing also](https://gist.github.com/abalanonline/9b128faa67e2459b765c1ef56454684b). I will raise a bug.\r\n",

    "created_at": "2017-05-06T15:32:05Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-05-06T15:33:21Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "There are two methods for calculating percentile: Nearest Rank method and Linear Interpolation Between Closest Ranks method.\r\nMedian equal to percentile 50 if interpolation method is used. But for JMeter measuring purposes the nearest rank percentile should be used because perc 90 gives the exact maximum time (not interpolated with some other values) for 90% of tests and this is what JMeter users are expecting.\r\nThis is why the median should be calculated separately (or we can implement interpolation method and use it for particular median purpose).\r\nBy the way getPercentPoint method is [failing also](https://gist.github.com/abalanonline/9b128faa67e2459b765c1ef56454684b). I will raise a bug.\r\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "created_at": "2017-05-06T15:32:05Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-05-06T15:33:21Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "There are two methods for calculating percentile: Nearest Rank method and Linear Interpolation Between Closest Ranks method.\r\nMedian equal to percentile 50 if interpolation method is used. But for JMeter measuring purposes the nearest rank percentile should be used because perc 90 gives the exact maximum time (not interpolated with some other values) for 90% of tests and this is what JMeter users are expecting.\r\nThis is why the median should be calculated separately (or we can implement interpolation method and use it for particular median purpose).\r\nBy the way getPercentPoint method is [failing also](https://gist.github.com/abalanonline/9b128faa67e2459b765c1ef56454684b). I will raise a bug.\r\n",

    "created_at": "2017-05-06T15:32:05Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-05-06T15:33:21Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "There are two methods for calculating percentile: Nearest Rank method and Linear Interpolation Between Closest Ranks method.\r\nMedian equal to percentile 50 if interpolation method is used. But for JMeter measuring purposes the nearest rank percentile should be used because perc 90 gives the exact maximum time (not interpolated with some other values) for 90% of tests and this is what JMeter users are expecting.\r\nThis is why the median should be calculated separately (or we can implement interpolation method and use it for particular median purpose).\r\nBy the way getPercentPoint method is [failing also](https://gist.github.com/abalanonline/9b128faa67e2459b765c1ef56454684b). I will raise a bug.\r\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "created_at": "2017-05-06T15:32:05Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-05-06T15:33:21Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "There are two methods for calculating percentile: Nearest Rank method and Linear Interpolation Between Closest Ranks method.\r\nMedian equal to percentile 50 if interpolation method is used. But for JMeter measuring purposes the nearest rank percentile should be used because perc 90 gives the exact maximum time (not interpolated with some other values) for 90% of tests and this is what JMeter users are expecting.\r\nThis is why the median should be calculated separately (or we can implement interpolation method and use it for particular median purpose).\r\nBy the way getPercentPoint method is [failing also](https://gist.github.com/abalanonline/9b128faa67e2459b765c1ef56454684b). I will raise a bug.\r\n",

    "created_at": "2017-05-06T15:32:05Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-05-06T15:33:21Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "There are two methods for calculating percentile: Nearest Rank method and Linear Interpolation Between Closest Ranks method.\r\nMedian equal to percentile 50 if interpolation method is used. But for JMeter measuring purposes the nearest rank percentile should be used because perc 90 gives the exact maximum time (not interpolated with some other values) for 90% of tests and this is what JMeter users are expecting.\r\nThis is why the median should be calculated separately (or we can implement interpolation method and use it for particular median purpose).\r\nBy the way getPercentPoint method is [failing also](https://gist.github.com/abalanonline/9b128faa67e2459b765c1ef56454684b). I will raise a bug.\r\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "@ppatierno I did a quick search in ReassignPartitionsCommand.scala and it seems that the version filed is not checked when the json file is parsed. So strictly speaking that version field is not currently mandatory for ReassignPartitionsCommand because we can provide a json file without version field to ReassignPartitionsCommand.\r\n\r\nI agreed that it is more obvious to user that version field is needed for ReassignPartitionsCommand because it is included in the generated json filed. But I think the actual reason we put version filed there is because we may need it in the future when we make backward incompatible change -- otherwise we don't even need to include it in the generated json file.\r\n\r\nThe need to prepare for potential backward incompatible change is shared between both ReassignPartitionsCommand and DeleteRecordsCommand. So I think for consistency reason we should either keep the version field in json file for all such tools, or remove it from all such tools. I think it is useful to have it there in general. Does this make sense?\r\n\r\n",

    "updated_at": "2017-09-28T13:04:43Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "@ppatierno I did a quick search in ReassignPartitionsCommand.scala and it seems that the version filed is not checked when the json file is parsed. So strictly speaking that version field is not currently mandatory for ReassignPartitionsCommand because we can provide a json file without version field to ReassignPartitionsCommand.\r\n\r\nI agreed that it is more obvious to user that version field is needed for ReassignPartitionsCommand because it is included in the generated json filed. But I think the actual reason we put version filed there is because we may need it in the future when we make backward incompatible change -- otherwise we don't even need to include it in the generated json file.\r\n\r\nThe need to prepare for potential backward incompatible change is shared between both ReassignPartitionsCommand and DeleteRecordsCommand. So I think for consistency reason we should either keep the version field in json file for all such tools, or remove it from all such tools. I think it is useful to have it there in general. Does this make sense?\r\n\r\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "@ppatierno I would prefer to check for the value of version field in both ReassignPartitionsCommand and DeleteRecordsCommand (any other tools if any). The version field defaults to 1 if it is not explicitly specified in the json file. As of now, the only valid value of version field for both tools is 1. If user specified any value different than 1, the tool should throw exception and exit.\r\n\r\nBy doing this we will keep the behavior backward compatible. I assume no (or very few) user will explicitly specify version field that is different than 1 in the json file. And we retain the capability to evolve the format of json file in the future by having this version filed.\r\n\r\n\r\n",
